[3] Salmonellosis, ox roast - USA (NY)
Date: Wed, 22 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: WIVB.com [edited]
<http://www.wivb.com/Global/story.asp?s=2333371>

Health department investigates apparent food poisoning
------------------------------------------------------
The Erie County Health Department is investigating some 80 cases of
apparent food poisoning, from the East Aurora Fire Company's annual Labor
Day ox roast. Officials suspect salmonella contamination in some of the
food served. There are about 15 confirmed salmonella cases so far.
Erie County Health Commissioner Dr Anthony Billittier said, "This is one of
those diseases that health care doesn't cure; they cure themselves, we just
try to make them feel better in the meantime." Most of the patients
complained of upset stomach and diarrhea.
The East Aurora fire chief says the health department inspects the food
before the ox roast each year.
[While it is indeed true that most cases of enteric non-typhoid
salmonellosis are self-limiting without specific therapy, significant
morbidity and mortality can occur in the elderly, infants, and in people
with impaired cellular immunity. It is not stated whether the ox meat
itself is felt to be the vehicle. Various food items were served, and an
epidemiological investigation would be needed to implicate a specific food.
- Mod.LL]
******
[4] Salmonellosis, waterborne - USA (MT)
Date: Wed, 22 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Billings (MT) Gazette [edited]
<http://www.billingsgazette.com/index.php?id=1&display=rednews/2004/09/22/build/state/70-poultry-pen.inc>

Water poisoning likely came from poultry pen
--------------------------------------------
A poultry pen is the likely source of drinking water contamination that
sickened at least 19 customers of a restaurant near St Ignatius and led to
its temporary closure, health officials say.
Dinnerbell Bakery and Banquets owner Glen Hochstetler said the Amish
restaurant with meals served family style will reopen when a new water
treatment system has state approval, perhaps early in Oct 2004. The
Dinnerbell closed in early Aug 2004. A new water system using chlorine will
ensure safe drinking water, said Eugene Pizzini, compliance officer for the
Montana Department of Environmental Quality.
At least 19 people experienced gastrointestinal problems severe enough for
them to seek medical attention, and were diagnosed with problems related to
salmonella bacteria, Pizzini said. Cases were reported as far away as Arizona.
Pizzini said an inspection revealed an illegally installed plumbing
connection that could have allowed backflow of water supplying a poultry
pen. The Dinnerbell had an ultraviolet light water treatment apparatus, and
it is possible failure of that system preceded the water contamination, he
said.
Regulators said that when the restaurant was being developed, an on-site
inspection of the plumbing system did not occur, but the engineering
drawings were reviewed. The link to the poultry pen was not in the drawings.
Hochstetler said the Dinnerbell was added to a farm plumbing system at the
time of the restaurant's construction a few years ago.
Pizzini anticipates no fines or other enforcement action. "We're not
looking to put anybody out of business," he said. "We want to make sure
that their water is meeting state standards."
[Although a poultry source for non-typhoid salmonellosis is certainly a
classic one, in this outbreak the bacteria spread through contaminated
water. - Mod.LL]
